# Commit messages

When proposing, writing, or amending **git commit messages** (including multi-commit splits), follow this exactly.

## Language

- **English only** for the subject line and body. Do not use Russian or other languages in commits.
- UI copy, docs, and user-facing strings in the app may stay localized; commits are not user-facing.

## Format (Conventional Commits)

```
<type>(optional scope): <short description>

[optional body]

[optional footer(s)]
```

- **type** (common): `feat`, `fix`, `docs`, `style`, `refactor`, `test`, `chore`, `perf`, `ci`, `build`, `revert`
- **scope**: optional, short noun — e.g. `history`, `rides`, `gpx`, `android` (lowercase)
- **description**: imperative mood, **no period** at the end, **~72 characters or fewer**, start lowercase after the colon space

## Examples

Good:

- `feat(history): add my rides and imported tabs with swipe`
- `fix(android): avoid pager-view codegen failure in CMake build`
- `chore(deps): sync package-lock.json`

Bad:

- `feat: История` (wrong language)
- `Fixed bug.` (not imperative; unnecessary period)
- `update stuff` (missing conventional type)

## Body and multiple commits

- Use the **body** to explain *why* or *what* changed when it is not obvious from the subject (bullet list is fine).
- When splitting work into several commits, give **each** commit its own conventional English subject; order commits logically (e.g. types/data before UI).

## Amending and hooks

- If the user’s environment appends lines via a git hook (e.g. `Made-with:`), do not remove them unless the user asks; focus your message on the conventional title and body above.
